  <div class="ct">
  
<p>One time, he got drunk enough to tell me about a crew of guys he went riding around with while they were in high school.</p>
<p>Waco, at that time, was rather segregated. &nbsp;Rather an understatement. &nbsp;His group of friends had parents who were in positions of influence, so they never got in trouble. &nbsp;This is the essence of the Jim Crow South. &nbsp;</p>
<p>They specifically chose to drive around in the &nbsp;black part of town. &nbsp;They used a baseball bat to knock mailboxes off of their posts by the road. &nbsp;But every now and then they say some poor black person walking by the side of the road who didn't hear them coming. &nbsp;They used the baseball bat on whoever that was. &nbsp;</p>
<p>That was an attitude that was deeply approved of back in those days. &nbsp;It isn't so overt now. &nbsp;Racists have learned to deny their racism. &nbsp;</p>
<p>But these attitudes still exist and they are a special burden to the Republican Party, which has been pandering to these people ever since LBJ signed the Voting Rights Act, creating a lot of resentful people who believe their privileged status has been damaged. &nbsp;</p>
<p>The entire exercise for the Heritage Foundation is how to pretend this isn't so.</p>

  </div>
